How to Write the Perfect Summary Section
Work backward, with your current or most recent job first.
Focus on major responsibilities and work achievements rather than daily tasks.
Summarize your experience with three to five punchy bullet points for each job listing.
Highlight skills and tasks that relate to the job you're applying to.
Use action verbs that give your achievements more power (e.g., “Managed team of 15 employees” instead of
responsible for a team of 15 employees”).
Give your accomplishments more weight by using numbers and metrics (e.g., Implemented new inventory
processes that cut overhead costs by 23%”).
